```
interface SelectProps<T> {
  placeholder?: string;
  options: T[];
  onChange: any;
}
```

This new interface takes in a type parameter `T` which can be any array of objects. You can then specify the type of `T` when using the interface. 

For example, if you wanted to use the interface for `MultiSelectParamProps`, you would do:

```
const multiSelectProps: SelectProps<SelectItem> = {
  placeholder: "Select an option",
  options: [{ label: "Option 1", value: "option1" }, { label: "Option 2", value: "option2" }],
  onChange: (selectedOption) => console.log(selectedOption)
}
```

And if you wanted to use it for `SelectProps`, you would do:

```
const selectProps: SelectProps<SendersContent> = {
  placeholder: "Select a sender",
  options: [{ id: 1, senderName: "Sender 1" }, { id: 2, senderName: "Sender 2" }],
  onChange: (selectedOption) => console.log(selectedOption)
}
``` 

This approach makes the interfaces more consistent, reusable and easier to use.

